.TH SMARTCXXCHECK 1 "2026-05-02" "smartmet-utils" "SmartMet Build Tools"
.SH NAME
smartcxxcheck \- detect C++ compiler vendor, major version and standard
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B smartcxxcheck
.RI [ compiler ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B smartcxxcheck
identifies the C++ compiler that the build will use and prints a
single space\(hyseparated line:
.PP
.RS 4
.IR compiler-id " " major-version " " cxx-std
.RE
.PP
where
.I compiler-id
is
.B g++
or
.BR clang++ ,
.I major-version
is the leading digit reported by the compiler, and
.I cxx-std
is one of
.BR c++17 " or " c++20 .
The output is consumed by the shared SmartMet
.B makefile.inc
to pick the C++ standard flag and to gate compiler\(hyspecific warnings
and workarounds.
.PP
Detection works by running
.B "\fIcompiler\fR \-x c++ \-E \-dM /dev/null"
and inspecting the predefined preprocessor macros
.RB ( __clang_major__ ", " __clang_version__ ", " __GNUC__ ", "
.BR __GNUC_MINOR__ ", " __cplusplus ).
For Clang, the matching system
.B /usr/bin/g++
is also probed to determine the C++ standard, since the SmartMet
build sticks to whatever standard the system GCC supports
.RB ( c++20
when GCC is 11 or newer,
.B c++17
when 8\(en10).
.PP
If detection fails for any reason, the script falls back to printing
a safe default of
.BI compiler " 0 c++17"
followed by a normal line, so callers always get a parsable result.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.I compiler
Name or absolute path of the compiler to probe. Defaults to
.BR g++ .
.SH EXAMPLES
Detect the system default:
.PP
.RS 4
smartcxxcheck
.RE
.PP
Detect a specific compiler:
.PP
.RS 4
smartcxxcheck /usr/bin/clang++
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR smartbuildcfg (1),
.BR g++ (1),
.BR clang++ (1),
.BR make (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Finnish Meteorological Institute
.PP
Report issues at <https://github.com/fmidev/smartmet-utils/issues>.
